# Continuity and the Intermediate Value Theorem

A function is continuous at $a$ when:

1. $f(a)$ exists;
2. $\lim_{x\to a}f(x)$ exists;
3. $\lim_{x\to a}f(x)=f(a)$.

The Intermediate Value Theorem says a continuous function takes every value between $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ on $[a,b]$.


> **Study habit:** translate every formula into a sentence about quantities and units.

:::mcf-end

